Abstract

The following notes/scripts/plots are inspired by Chapter 3 Data Pre-processing Exercises 3-3 of Applied Predictive Modeling by Max Kuhn and Kjell Johnson.

library(knitr)
library(data.table)
library(ggplot2)
library(caret)
library(grid)
library(gtable)
library(RregressPkg)
library(RplotterPkg)

The BloodBrain Dataset

(a) Load the data

data(BloodBrain, package = "caret")
bb_dt <- data.table::as.data.table(bbbDescr)

(b) Degenerate distributions?

  1. Are there any NA values?
anyNA(bbbDescr)
## [1] FALSE
  1. Plot frequency distributions:
RplotterPkg::multi_bar_plot(
  df = bb_dt,
  variables = colnames(bb_dt),
  columns = 8,
  col_width = 1.8,
  row_height = 1.8
)

The following have either very small variance or are nearly constant and would not make good predictors: negative, a_acid, frac.anion7., alert, inthb

  1. Remove the low variance predictors:
bb_dt <- bb_dt[, !c("negative", "a_acid", "frac.anion7.", "alert", "inthb")]

(c) Are there strong relationships between the predictors?

  1. Call RregressPkg::low_predictor_collinearity() to identify predictors with low collinearity:
bbb_cor <- stats::cor(bb_dt)
results_lst <- RregressPkg::low_predictor_collinearity(bbb_cor)
  1. The function identified 58 predictors with low collinearity. Keep these predictors in the data frame:
predictors <- results_lst$predictors
bb_dt <- bb_dt[, ..predictors]
  1. Compute the PCA involving the remaining 58 predictors. Scale the input and set the maximum number of components to 2:
pca <- stats::prcomp(x = bb_dt, scale. = T, rank. = 2)
  1. The accounting of variance for the 4 components:
pca_loads_dt <- data.table(
  Predictor = c("tcsa","prx","ctaa","rncg"),
  PCA_1 = c(-.27,-.27,-.09,-.06),
  PCA_2 = c(-.02,-.06,-.29,.28)
)
RplotterPkg::create_table(
  x = pca_loads_dt,
  full_width = T,
  caption = "Principal Component Loadings",
  footnote_title = "Component variance:",
  footnote = "PCA_1: 8.82; PCA_2: 7.84"
)
Principal Component Loadings
Predictor PCA_1 PCA_2
tcsa -0.27 -0.02
prx -0.27 -0.06
ctaa -0.09 -0.29
rncg -0.06 0.28
Component variance:
PCA_1: 8.82; PCA_2: 7.84
  1. Plot the pca:
pca_plot <- RregressPkg::plot_pca(
  df = bb_dt,
  center = T,
  scale. = T,
  rank. = 2,
  measures = colnames(bb_dt),
  pca_pair = c("PC1", "PC2"),
  show_meas_table = F,
  display_plot = F
)
pca_plot$loadings_plot
